.TH TTPX 1 "2026-05-13" "ttpx" "Security Research Tools"
.SH NAME
ttpx \- Tactics, Techniques, Payloads & Exploits \(em search HackTricks and PayloadsAllTheThings for exploitation techniques; generate CSRF PoC files
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B ttpx
.B \-l
[
.B \-\-since
.I N[d]
]
.br
.B ttpx
.B \-u
.br
.B ttpx
.B \-f
.I TERM
[
.I TERM
\&...]
.br
.B ttpx
.B \-p
.I TERM
[
.I TERM
\&...]
[
.B \-d
.I CONTEXT
]
.br
.B ttpx
.B \-m
.I PATH
[
.B \-s
.I TERM
]
.br
.B ttpx
.B \-\-csrf
.I FILE
[
.B \-\-bypass
]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B ttpx
searches local clones of HackTricks and PayloadsAllTheThings (PATT) for
exploitation techniques matching all provided search terms.
.PP
Use
.B \-l
to browse all top\-level categories in both sources without search terms.
Use
.B \-u
to pull the latest commits from both knowledge bases and print a change summary.
Use
.B \-f
to browse matching entries as a clean table (fast, no API cost).
Use
.B \-p
to send the matching content to Claude and receive a single,
syntax\-highlighted, ready\-to\-use payload with a recommendation.
Feed back errors or context with
.B \-d
to get an adapted payload on the next attempt.
Use
.B \-m
to copy a file from a
.B \-f
result to the current directory as plain text with markdown stripped.
Optionally scope the output to a specific section with
.BR \-s .
.PP
Use
.B \-\-csrf
to parse a raw HTTP request file (Burp or Caido format) and generate a
self-contained CSRF proof-of-concept HTML file
.RI ( csrf_poc.html )
in the current directory.
The PoC type is selected automatically based on the request's Content-Type:
a form-urlencoded POST becomes an auto-submitting HTML form, a JSON POST
becomes a
.B fetch()
call, a GET becomes an
.B <img>
tag, and a multipart POST becomes a FormData skeleton.
No API call is made by default.
After generating the PoC, the request is automatically checked for known
CSRF token field names (form-encoded and JSON bodies) and headers; a warning
is printed if any are found.
Add
.B \-\-bypass
to send the request to Claude for targeted bypass analysis.
The offline token detection results are passed directly into the prompt so
Claude skips re-detection: if a token was found, it focuses on stripping,
leakage, and Content-Type manipulation; if none was found, it focuses on
SameSite enforcement, Origin/Referer validation, and whether the offline
PoC is already sufficient.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BR \-l ", " \-\-list
List all top\-level directories in both HackTricks and PayloadsAllTheThings.
No search terms needed. Use this to explore available categories before
narrowing down with
.BR \-f .
Each source prints a footer with its category count.
Combine with
.B \-\-since
to filter to recently updated categories.
.TP
.BR \-u ", " \-\-update
Run
.B git pull \-\-ff\-only
on both knowledge bases and print a per\-source change summary (files changed,
insertions, deletions). Use this to keep payloads current before an engagement.
.TP
.BR \-\-since " " \fIN[d]\fR
Optional. Use with
.B \-l
to filter the category list to directories that have had commits in the last
.I N
days (e.g.
.B \-\-since 7d
or
.BR \-\-since\ 7 ).
The footer shows how many categories matched out of the total.
.TP
.BR \-f ", " \-\-find " " \fITERM\fR " [" \fITERM\fR ...]"
Search both sources for files containing all specified terms. Displays a
table with source tag, matched section title, and relative file path.
No Claude call is made. Fast and offline\-capable.
.TP
.BR \-p ", " \-\-payload " " \fITERM\fR " [" \fITERM\fR ...]"
Search both sources for files containing all specified terms, then send
the matched content to Claude. Claude selects the single most impactful
payload, syntax\-highlights it by language (JavaScript, PHP, Groovy,
Bash, Python, Java), and provides a one\-line recommendation.
A raw copy\-paste block is printed below the highlighted view for safe terminal selection.
Requires
.BR ANTHROPIC_API_KEY .
.TP
.BR \-m ", " \-\-mirror " " \fIPATH\fR
Copy a file to the current directory as plain text with markdown stripped.
.I PATH
is the relative path exactly as shown in a
.B \-f
result. Paths with spaces must be quoted.
.TP
.BR \-s ", " \-\-section " " \fITERM\fR
Optional. Use with
.B \-m
to extract only the section whose heading contains
.IR TERM .
Extracts from the matched heading down to the next heading of equal or
higher level. Falls back to the full file if no matching heading is found.
.TP
.BR \-d ", " \-\-details " " \fICONTEXT\fR
Optional. Pass error output or additional context from a previous
.B \-p
attempt. Claude will analyse the failure and produce an adapted payload.
The output includes a
.B "What changed"
section listing the specific tokens or lines modified from the previous attempt.
Repeat
.B \-d
to chain multiple error contexts across attempts (e.g.
.BR "\-d \(dqerr1\(dq \-d \(dqerr2\(dq" ).
Only meaningful with
.BR \-p .
.TP
.BR \-\-no\-log
Skip auto\-logging this
.B \-p
result to
.IR ~/Tools/ttpx-session.log .
By default every
.B \-p
call appends a timestamped entry (terms, vulnerability, first payload line) to that log.
.TP
.BR \-\-csrf " " \fIFILE\fR
Parse a raw HTTP request file and generate a self-contained CSRF PoC HTML
file saved as
.I csrf_poc.html
in the current directory.
.I FILE
should be a plain-text file containing the raw request as copied from Burp
Suite or Caido (request line, headers, blank line, optional body).
The PoC type is selected by Content-Type:
.RS
.IP \(bu 4
form-urlencoded \(em auto-submitting HTML
.B <form>
with hidden inputs
.IP \(bu 4
application/json \(em
.B fetch()
call with
.B credentials: 'include'
and a CORS note
.IP \(bu 4
multipart/form-data \(em
.B FormData
.B fetch()
skeleton (fields must be filled manually)
.IP \(bu 4
GET \(em
.B <img>
tag for zero-click delivery
.RE
.RS
No API call is made. Field names, values, and the target URL are HTML-escaped
in the generated output. After the PoC is written, the request is
automatically scanned for known CSRF token field names and headers; a warning
is printed with the field name, location, and a hint to use
.B \-\-bypass
if any are found.
Detection covers form-encoded bodies, top-level JSON keys, and request headers.
The heuristic also fires on form-encoded bodies when the
.B Content-Type
header is absent, as long as
.B =
is present in the body.
Common frameworks detected include Django, Rails, ASP.NET, Laravel, WordPress,
and Ant Design; headers checked include
.BR X-CSRF-Token ,
.BR X-XSRF-Token ,
.BR X-CSRFToken ,
.BR X-Request-Token ,
and
.BR X-Ant-CSRF-Token .
.PP
.B Note:
tokens in nested JSON objects, multipart fields, and cookies are not detected.
A clean warning does not guarantee the endpoint has no CSRF protection.
.RE
.TP
.BR \-\-bypass
Optional. Use with
.B \-\-csrf
to call Claude for targeted CSRF bypass analysis.
The offline token detection results are fed into the prompt so Claude goes
straight to strategy without re-deriving what is already known.
When a token is present, suggestions focus on stripping or predicting the
token, leaking it via CORS or XSS, Content-Type manipulation to avoid CORS
preflight, and method override tricks.
When no token is detected, suggestions focus on SameSite cookie enforcement,
Origin/Referer header validation, Content-Type restrictions, and whether the
generated PoC is already sufficient to exploit the target.
Requires
.BR ANTHROPIC_API_KEY .
Use
.B \-\-bypass
when the offline PoC fails and you want to understand what defence is
blocking it.
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
.B ANTHROPIC_API_KEY
Required when using
.BR \-p " / " \-\-payload
or
.BR \-\-bypass .
Obtain from console.anthropic.com.
.SH FILES
.TP
.I ~/Tools/hacktricks
Local clone of the HackTricks knowledge base.
Clone with:
.B git clone https://github.com/HackTricks\-wiki/hacktricks ~/Tools/hacktricks
.TP
.I ~/Tools/payloadsallthethings
Local clone of PayloadsAllTheThings.
Clone with:
.B git clone https://github.com/swisskyrepo/PayloadsAllTheThings ~/Tools/payloadsallthethings
.SH EXAMPLES
Browse categories (update sources first):
.PP
.RS
.nf
ttpx \-u
ttpx \-l
ttpx \-l \-\-since 7d
.fi
.RE
.PP
Browse matching entries before committing to a payload:
.PP
.RS
.nf
ttpx \-f ssti handlebars
ttpx \-f lfi php windows iis
.fi
.RE
.PP
Generate a payload directly:
.PP
.RS
.nf
ttpx \-p ssti handlebars groovy rce
ttpx \-p sqli union mysql
ttpx \-p xss csp bypass reflected
ttpx \-p lfi php windows iis read
.fi
.RE
.PP
Adapt after a failed attempt:
.PP
.RS
.nf
ttpx \-p ssti handlebars groovy rce \-d "'require' is not defined"
ttpx \-p sqli union mysql \-d "WAF blocking SELECT and UNION keywords"
ttpx \-p lfi php \-d "../etc/passwd filtered, server returned 403"
.fi
.RE
.PP
Mirror a file from a \-f result (full file):
.PP
.RS
.nf
ttpx \-m "Server Side Template Injection/JavaScript.md"
.fi
.RE
.PP
Mirror a specific section only:
.PP
.RS
.nf
ttpx \-m "Server Side Template Injection/JavaScript.md" \-s handlebars
ttpx \-m "File Inclusion/README.md" \-s php
.fi
.RE
.PP
Generate a CSRF PoC from a captured request:
.PP
.RS
.nf
ttpx \-\-csrf req.txt                   # offline PoC, no API cost
ttpx \-\-csrf req.txt \-\-bypass          # PoC + Claude bypass analysis
.fi
.RE
.PP
Typical workflow:
.PP
.RS
.nf
ttpx \-u                                                        # keep sources current
ttpx \-l \-\-since 7d                                             # browse recent updates
ttpx \-f ssti handlebars                                        # see what files match
ttpx \-m "Server Side Template Injection/JavaScript.md" \-s handlebars  # grab the section
ttpx \-p ssti handlebars groovy                                  # generate a payload
ttpx \-p ssti handlebars groovy \-d "'require' is not defined"    # adapt after error
.fi
.RE
.SH NOTES
All search terms are AND\-matched against file content (case\-insensitive).
More specific terms return fewer files and produce more focused payloads.
If
.B \-p
returns no results, drop a term and try again.
.PP
Each
.B \-p
call costs approximately $0.001\(en$0.005 in Claude API credits
(claude\-sonnet\-4\-6, ~200\(en500 tokens output).
Each
.B \-\-bypass
call costs approximately $0.001\(en$0.002
(~200\(en400 tokens output).
.B \-f ,
.B \-m ,
and
.B \-\-csrf
without
.B \-\-bypass
are free.
